# 16 : DUAL-SURFACE — CSLv3-native + Rust-hybrid, unified HIR
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

§ THESIS
  CSSLv3 accepts TWO surface syntaxes that parse to SAME HIR :
    CSLv3-native  : density=sovereignty, Apocky+Claude primary
    Rust-hybrid   : conventional-ergonomic, external-contributor bridge
  both semantically-identical • formatter round-trips between them
  cross-reference : CSLv3 parser (cslparser pkg) reused via §§ 14_CSSLv3_BRIDGE.csl

§ MODE-DETECTION
  file-extension signal : .cssl-csl | .cssl-rust | .cssl (auto-detect)
  first-non-comment-line signal :
    starts with § + glyph → CSLv3-native
    starts with `module` | `use` | `fn` | `struct` → Rust-hybrid
    ambiguous : default Rust-hybrid, warn + recommend explicit
  per-file-pragma :
    #![surface = "csl"]  or  #![surface = "rust"]
  mixed-mode forbidden within single file (would-confuse tooling)

§ RUST-HYBRID SURFACE
  detailed in §§ 09_SYNTAX (primary specification)
  conventional : keywords + braces + explicit-syntax
  target audience : external contributors, docs, tutorials, onboarding

§ CSLv3-NATIVE SURFACE
  based on : CSLv3 repo C:\Users\Apocky\source\repos\CSLv3
  tokenizer : 71-glyph table (§§ 12_TOKENIZER.csl of CSLv3 repo)
  grammar : §§ 13_GRAMMAR_SELF.csl of CSLv3 repo
  compound-operators : .(of) +(and) -(that-is) ⊗(having) @(at)
  morpheme-stacking : 'd 'f 's 't 'e 'm 'p 'g 'r suffixes
  evidence-markers : ✓ ◐ ○ ✗ ⊘ △ ▽ ‼
  modals : W! R! M? N! I> Q?
  think-blocks : §P (process) §D (design) §T (theorem) §S (specification) §C (code)

§ DUAL-SURFACE EXAMPLE : same fn both-surfaces

  # Rust-hybrid form
  @differentiable
  @lipschitz(k = 1.0)
  fn sphere_sdf(p : vec3, r : f32'pos) -> f32 {
    length(p) - r
  }

  # CSLv3-native form
  § sphere_sdf ≡ @differentiable ⊗ @lipschitz<k=1.0>
    I> length(p).(of).vec3 - r.(of).f32'pos
    → f32
    ✓ Lipschitz-1 by-construction
    ✓ @differentiable ⇒ bwd_diff yields O(1) normal

  both → same HIR node :
    HirFn {
      name: "sphere_sdf",
      attrs: [@differentiable, @lipschitz(1.0)],
      params: [(p, vec3), (r, f32{v : f32 | v > 0})],
      return: f32,
      body: Sub(Length(p), r),
      effect_row: ⟨⟩,
      ifc_label: ⊥,
      cap: val,
    }

§ DUAL-SURFACE EXAMPLE : fn with effects

  # Rust-hybrid
  @staged
  fn render_scene<S : Scene>(cam : Camera) -> Image
    / {GPU, Deadline<16ms>, NoAlloc, Power<225mW>, Telemetry<Counters>}
  {
    for (x, y) in grid(cam.size) |> parallel {
      let ray = cam.ray(x, y)
      let hit = ray_march::<S>(ray) ?: return background()
      emit pixel(x, y, shade(hit, bwd_diff(S::eval_sdf)(hit.pos)))
    }
  }

  # CSLv3-native
  § render_scene<S.(of).Scene> ≡ @staged
    → Image.(of).cam.(of).Camera
    / ⟨ GPU ⊗ Deadline<16ms> ⊗ NoAlloc ⊗ Power<225mW> ⊗ Telemetry<Counters> ⟩
    §P §§ for-pixel
      (x,y).∈ grid.(of).cam.size ▷ parallel
      ray ≡ cam.ray(x,y)
      hit ≡ ray_march<S>(ray) ? : return background()
      emit pixel(x, y, shade(hit, bwd_diff(S::eval_sdf)(hit.pos)))
    ✓ specialized per-Scene @ compile

§ PARSER UNIFICATION (HIR)
  each surface has its own lexer + parser → distinct CST
  each CST → elaborator → unified HIR
  downstream (MIR, LIR, codegen) : surface-agnostic
  diagnostic : errors reference original surface (source-map preserved)

§ FORMATTER (csslfmt --mode=X)
  modes :
    --mode=rust-hybrid        canonical Rust-hybrid form
    --mode=csl-native         canonical CSLv3-native form
    --mode=rust-compact       minimal-whitespace Rust-hybrid
    --mode=csl-dense          maximal-compression CSLv3 (Apocky-preferred)
    --mode=literate           markdown-with-code-blocks
    --mode=ascii-only         no Unicode glyphs (for legacy tooling)
  round-trip invariant : mode-X → mode-Y → mode-X reproduces original

§ IDE + LSP INTEGRATION
  both surfaces get : syntax-highlight, autocomplete, hover, goto-def,
                      diagnostic-lenses, rename, formatting
  LSP server (stage0) : single server, surface-detect-per-buffer
  VS Code extension : one extension, both surfaces
  tree-sitter grammars : one for each surface
  reuse cslparser (from CSLv3 repo) for CSLv3-native surface

§ CROSS-SURFACE CITATION
  in Rust-hybrid : `§ I> ...` comments embed CSLv3-CoT
  in CSLv3-native : `§C ... §C` blocks embed Rust-hybrid code-fragments
  both pass through tooling transparently

§ MIGRATION WORKFLOW
  Apocky writes in CSLv3-native @ high velocity
  csslfmt --mode=rust-hybrid → external-docs extracted
  both forms checked-into repo (canonical = CSLv3-native for Apocky-repos)
  CI verifies round-trip

§ RATIONALE FOR DUAL
  single-surface : forces tradeoff
    CSLv3-native only : external onboarding blocked
    Rust-hybrid only : Apocky loses density-sovereignty
  dual-surface : no-tradeoff, one-time parser-doubling cost
  HIR-unified : all downstream work shared

§ DEPENDENCIES
  CSLv3 parser/cslparser package (canonical, §§ 14_CSSLv3_BRIDGE of CSLv3 repo)
  csslfmt (CSSLv3 formatter, new, lives in CSSLv3/compiler-rs/src/fmt/)
  LSP server (§§ 23 testing ties in for diagnostics)
  tree-sitter grammars (external, versioned with compiler)

∎ DUAL_SURFACE
